<body>
    <h1>Scheduled Tasks</h1>
    <div class=3D"Section1">
        <h1 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-ScheduledTasks">Scheduled Tasks</h1>
<p>Run Claude on autopilot. Set it up once, and it does the work for you on=
 the cadence you want =E2=80=94 every morning, every Monday, the first of e=
very month.</p>
<p>Owner: Charlie Delamare<br>
Audience: Anyone at Mews who's set up Claude<br>
Estimated reading time: 5 minutes</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-What'sascheduledtask?">What's a scheduled task?</h=
2>
<p>A <strong>scheduled task</strong> is a saved instruction that Claude run=
s on its own =E2=80=94 without you having to open the app or type the promp=
t.</p>
<p>You give it three things:</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>A <strong>prompt</strong> (what you want Claude to do)</p></li>
<li>
<p>A <strong>schedule</strong> (when to do it =E2=80=94 every Monday at 9am=
, every hour, the 1st of each month)</p></li>
<li>
<p>An <strong>output destination</strong> (post the result to Slack, email =
it to you, save it to Confluence, drop it in a folder)</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Claude wakes up at the right time, does the work, delivers the result, a=
nd goes back to sleep until next time.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Whentoreachforascheduledtask">When to reach for a =
scheduled task</h2>
<p>Three rules of thumb:</p>
<p><strong>1. You do the same thing on a regular cadence.</strong> Weekly u=
pdates, daily digests, monthly reports =E2=80=94 anything you find yourself=
 doing on a calendar.</p>
<p><strong>2. The work would be the same whether you started it or Claude d=
id.</strong> Pulling data, summarising channels, drafting standard messages=
 =E2=80=94 tasks where the <em>thinking</em> is the same every time.</p>
<p><strong>3. You'd rather see the output than do the work.</strong> A sche=
duled task isn't free =E2=80=94 it costs tokens every run. Use it when you =
actually want the output, not just because automation feels cool.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Usecases=E2=80=94stealthese">Use cases =E2=80=94 s=
teal these</h2>
<p>A starter list. Each one is a real schedule someone at Mews has running =
(or could).</p>
<h3 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Daily">Daily</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Morning prep brief</strong> =E2=80=94 every weekday at 8am, pull=
 today's calendar, look up each external attendee in Salesforce, surface an=
ything notable from Gong, post a one-pager to your DMs.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Overnight Slack digest</strong> =E2=80=94 every weekday at 9am, =
summarise everything from <code>#team-ce-announce</code>, <code>#engineerin=
g-announce</code>, and your DMs from the last 16 hours. Post it as a thread=
 to your own DM.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>End-of-day Gong recap</strong> =E2=80=94 every weekday at 6pm, p=
ull all your calls from today, write a 3-line summary of each, save to a Co=
nfluence page called "[Your name] =E2=80=94 daily call notes".</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Inbox triage</strong> =E2=80=94 every weekday at 9am, scan unrea=
d emails from the last 24 hours, flag anything that needs a response today,=
 post the flagged list to your DMs.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Weekly">Weekly</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Monday morning rollup</strong> =E2=80=94 every Monday at 8am, wr=
ite your weekly update post (calendar, commits, key threads from Slack) and=
 post it as a draft in your team channel.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Friday wrap-up</strong> =E2=80=94 every Friday at 5pm, pull what=
 shipped this week from Linear/Jira, post a "what happened this week" summa=
ry to your team channel.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Pipeline risk check</strong> =E2=80=94 every Monday at 7am, run =
the pipeline risk report from Salesforce, post deals at risk to <code>#sale=
s-leadership</code>.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Customer at-risk scan</strong> =E2=80=94 every Wednesday morning=
, look at customer health signals (Common Room, recent Gong calls, support =
tickets), DM you any accounts that look wobbly.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Monthly">Monthly</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Sandbox pipeline health</strong> =E2=80=94 on the 10th of each m=
onth, cross-reference accounts that used the Mews Sandbox with Salesforce o=
pps, post the at-risk list as a Slack canvas.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Skills library audit</strong> =E2=80=94 first of the month, list=
 every skill in your library, flag any that haven't been used in 60 days fo=
r cleanup.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Token usage report</strong> =E2=80=94 first of the month, pull l=
ast month's usage, summarise where you spent most credits, post to your DMs=
.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Customer health rollup</strong> =E2=80=94 first of the month, sc=
an all named accounts, surface any that have changed status (renewed, churn=
ed, expanded), post to leadership.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Quarterly">Quarterly</h3>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>End-of-quarter team recap</strong> =E2=80=94 last Friday of each=
 quarter, pull what the team shipped, what closed, key wins, format as a Co=
nfluence page draft, ping the team for review.</p></li>
</ul>
<h3 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-One-offs(stilluseful)">One-offs (still useful)</h3=
>
<ul>
<li>
<p><strong>Pre-meeting prep, 1 hour before</strong> =E2=80=94 for a specifi=
c high-stakes meeting, schedule a one-time task to run an hour before the m=
eeting and DM you a brief.</p></li>
<li>
<p><strong>Weekend project tracker</strong> =E2=80=94 Saturday morning, sum=
marise where your side project / personal task list stands.</p></li>
</ul>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Howtocreateascheduledtask">How to create a schedul=
ed task</h2>
<p>The easiest way: just ask Claude.</p>
<h3 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-InChatorCo-work">In Chat or Co-work</h3>
<p>Type something like:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Schedule this to run every Monday at 8am Prague time:</p>
<p>Pull my calendar for the week ahead. For each external meeting, look up =
the company in Salesforce and the most recent Gong calls. Write a one-page =
Word doc prep brief for me and DM it to me on Slack.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Claude will:</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Confirm what it understood (cadence, prompt, output destination)</p></li=
>
<li>
<p>Check it has the connectors and permissions it needs to actually run</p>=
</li>
<li>
<p>Save the schedule</p></li>
<li>
<p>Tell you when it'll run for the first time</p></li>
</ol>
<p>That's it. It's now running on its own.</p>
<h3 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Anatomyofagoodscheduledtaskprompt">Anatomy of a go=
od scheduled task prompt</h3>
<p>Give it everything a smart colleague would need to do the work without a=
sking you a question:</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table data-layout=3D"default" class=3D"confluenceTable">
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Ingredient</p></th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">
<p>Example</p></th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>What to do</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>"Summarise this week's customer-facing Slack channels"</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Where to pull from</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>"<code>#customer-feedback</code>, <code>#cs-team</code>, <code>#renewals=
</code>"</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>How to format</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>"Three sections: themes, escalations, wins. Max 200 words."</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Where to send it</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>"DM it to me on Slack"</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Voice / style (optional)</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>"Use my 'How I write on Slack' skill"</p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p><strong>Edge cases</strong></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">
<p>"If nothing happened this week, just say 'quiet week' =E2=80=94 don't pa=
d."</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Commoncadencesyntax">Common cadence syntax</h2>
<p>You can describe cadence in plain English =E2=80=94 Claude will understa=
nd:</p>
<ul>
<li>
<p>"every weekday at 9am"</p></li>
<li>
<p>"every Monday at 8am Prague time"</p></li>
<li>
<p>"every hour"</p></li>
<li>
<p>"the 1st of every month at 7am"</p></li>
<li>
<p>"every Friday at 5pm"</p></li>
<li>
<p>"every 15 minutes" <em>(don't actually do this =E2=80=94 see Tips below)=
</em></p></li>
<li>
<p>"next Monday at 9am, then every Monday after that"</p></li>
</ul>
<p>Always <strong>specify a timezone</strong> if it matters. Default is wha=
tever your Claude account's timezone is set to.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Howtomanageyourschedules">How to manage your sched=
ules</h2>
<h3 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Seewhatyouhaverunning">See what you have running</=
h3>
<p>In Chat, ask:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>List my scheduled tasks.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Claude will show you each one =E2=80=94 name, cadence, next run time, la=
st result.</p>
<h3 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Pause,edit,ordelete">Pause, edit, or delete</h3>
<blockquote>
<p>Pause my Monday morning rollup.</p>
<p>Change the morning prep brief to run at 7:30 instead of 8am.</p>
<p>Delete the overnight Slack digest.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>You can also do this in <strong>Settings =E2=86=92 Scheduled tasks</stro=
ng> in the desktop app.</p>
<h3 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Seethehistory">See the history</h3>
<p>Each scheduled task keeps a log of past runs =E2=80=94 what Claude did, =
what it produced, any errors. Good for debugging when something stops worki=
ng.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Tipsthatsaveyouheadaches">Tips that save you heada=
ches</h2>
<p><strong>Test the prompt manually first.</strong> Before scheduling, just=
 run the prompt in Chat once. Make sure the output is what you want. If it'=
s not, fix the prompt =E2=80=94 don't schedule a thing that gives you garba=
ge twice a week.</p>
<p><strong>Specify the output destination explicitly.</strong> "Post to Sla=
ck" is ambiguous =E2=80=94 Slack where? Be specific: "DM it to me", "post i=
n <code>#my-channel</code>", "save as a draft in <code>#sales-leadership</c=
ode>".</p>
<p><strong>Use Slack drafts for anything that goes to a public channel.</st=
rong> Scheduled posts that go straight to a channel can be embarrassing if =
the schedule misfires. Drafts let you eyeball before sending.</p>
<p><strong>Don't over-schedule.</strong> Every run costs tokens. A daily ta=
sk running for a year is 365 runs =E2=80=94 make sure you actually need tha=
t cadence. Most "weekly" things should be weekly, not daily.</p>
<p><strong>Set permissions before you schedule.</strong> Scheduled tasks ru=
n when you're not at the keyboard. If the connector tools aren't on <strong=
>Always Allow</strong>, the task will hit a permission prompt with no-one h=
ome and silently fail. See the <strong>Set your tool permissions</strong> s=
tep in the <a href=3D"https://mews.atlassian.net/wiki/spaces/GTMS/pages/192=
3842874/Getting+Started+with+Claude+Setup+Guide" data-linked-resource-id=3D=
"1923842874" data-linked-resource-version=3D"14" data-linked-resource-type=
=3D"page">setup guide</a>.</p>
<p><strong>Add a "nothing to report" guard.</strong> Scheduled tasks that r=
un on slow weeks can produce padded, noisy output. Add: "If there's nothing=
 meaningful to report, just say 'quiet week' and stop."</p>
<p><strong>Keep one eye on usage.</strong> Schedules can quietly burn throu=
gh credits. Glance at <strong>Settings =E2=86=92 Usage</strong> every week =
or two, especially in the first month after you set things up.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Aworkedexample">A worked example</h2>
<p>Here's the full anatomy of a real scheduled task =E2=80=94 a Monday morn=
ing weekly prep brief.</p>
<p><strong>Prompt:</strong></p>
<blockquote>
<p>For the week ahead, do the following:</p>
<ol start=3D"1">
<li>
<p>Pull my Outlook calendar for Monday=E2=80=93Friday</p></li>
<li>
<p>For each external meeting (anyone not on <code>@mews.com</code>), look u=
p the company in Salesforce =E2=80=94 pull stage, ARR, last activity</p></l=
i>
<li>
<p>For each company, find our 3 most recent Gong calls and summarise the ke=
y themes</p></li>
<li>
<p>Write a one-page Word doc per meeting, named <code>[Day] =E2=80=94 [Comp=
any] prep</code></p></li>
<li>
<p>Post a Slack DM to me with: today's date, a numbered list of meetings, a=
nd a link to each prep doc</p></li>
</ol>
<p>Tone: my "How I write on Slack" skill.<br>
If I have no external meetings this week, just DM "quiet week ahead =E2=80=
=94 nothing to prep."</p>
</blockquote>
<p><strong>Cadence:</strong> Every Monday at 7:30am Prague time.</p>
<p><strong>Output destination:</strong> Slack DM to me, plus prep docs save=
d to my OneDrive in <code>Claude/Weekly Prep/[year-week]/</code>.</p>
<p><strong>Permissions needed (set to Always Allow):</strong> Outlook (read=
 calendar), Salesforce (query), Gong (read calls), Word (create doc), OneDr=
ive (write file), Slack (send DM).</p>
<p>That's the whole thing. Set it up once, and every Monday morning you wal=
k into your week already prepped.</p>
<hr>
<h2 id=3D"ScheduledTasks-Gotquestions?">Got questions?</h2>
<p>Ask Claude =E2=80=94 "help me schedule X every Monday" is one of the thi=
ngs it's best at.</p>
<p>Or ping me on Slack: <strong>@Charlie Delamare</strong>.<br>
Or post in <strong>#ran-ai</strong> so the team can see the answer.</p>
    </div>
</body>
</html>
